9","1430–1470":"1430–1470","1430–Female":"1430–Overleden","1440–Female":"1440–Overleden","1442–Male":"1442–Overleden","1415–1449":"1415–1449","1435–Male":"1435–Overleden","1445–1536":"1445–1536","1396–1452":"1396–1452","1400–1492":"1400–1492","1396":"1396","1440":"1440","1492":"1492","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1536":"1536","1415":"1415","1435":"1435","1424":"1424","1445":"1445","1400":"1400","1442":"1442","1452":"1452","1430":"1430","1509":"1509","1419":"1419","1429":"1429","1449":"1449","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England":"England","Rugge, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1419–1445":"1419–1445","1424–1480":"1424–1480","1424–1509":"1424–1509","1429–1509":"1429–1509","1430–1470":"1430–1470","1430–Female":"1430–Deceased","1440–Female":"1440–Deceased","1442–Male":"1442–Deceased","1415–1449":"1415–1449","1435–Male":"1435–Deceased","1445–1536":"1445–1536","1396–1452":"1396–1452","1400–1492":"1400–1492","1396":"1396","1440":"1440","1492":"1492","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1536":"1536","1415":"1415","1435":"1435","1424":"1424","1445":"1445","1400":"1400","1442":"1442","1452":"1452","1430":"1430","1509":"1509","1419":"1419","1429":"1429","1449":"1449","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England":"England","Rugge, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wright","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name for a craftsman or maker of machinery, mostly in wood, of any of a wide range of kinds, from Middle English and Older Scots <i>wriht</i>, <i>wright</i>, <i>wricht</i>, <i>writh</i>, <i>write</i> (Old English <i>wyrhta</i>, <i>wryhta</i>) ‘craftsman’, especially ‘carpenter, joiner’. The term is found in various combinations (for example,   Cartwright   and   Wainwright  ), but when used in isolation it often referred to a builder of windmills or watermills. This surname is also very common among African Americans."],"variants":[{"name":"Wrights","meanings":["(1997: 103;2007: 204; 2010: NA)","English: variant of   Wright  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Wrightsman","meanings":["Probably English (although no longer found in Britain), meaning‘servant of the wright’ (see   Wright  )."]},{"name":"Cartwright","meanings":["English (Midlands and northern England): occupational name from Middle English <i>cart(e)</i> ‘cart’ + <i>wright(e)</i> ‘craftsman’ (Old English <i>cræt</i> or Old Norse <i>kartr</i> + Old English <i>wyrhta</i>), for a cartwright, a maker of carts.","Variant of   Courtright  , a surname of Dutch origin."]},{"name":"Wrightson","meanings":["English (northern England, especially Durham): patronymic from   Wright  , meaning ‘son of the wright’."]},{"name":"Right","meanings":["(2007: 493; 2010: NA)","English: variant of   Wright  ."]},{"name":"McWright","meanings":["Scottish or Irish: Gaelic patronymic with the English and Scots occupational term   Wright  , meaning ‘son of the wright’. The name is possibly a part translation of   McIntyre  , which fully translates as ‘son of the wright’."]},{"name":"Wrightman","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>wright</i> ‘craftsman’ (see   Wright  ) + <i>man</i> ‘man’, denoting someone who assisted a craftsman."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Maria</i> via Old Welsh <i>Meir</i>.  See  <b>Mary</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mary Ellen Wright was born in 1419, in Shropshire, England, her father, Lord Rev. Thomas Wright, was 23 and her mother, Lady Agnes Hunt, was 19. She had at least 2 sons with William Rugge. She died in 1445, in England, at the age of 26."},"et":{"1419–1445":"1419–1445","1424–1480":"1424–1480","1424–1509":"1424–1509","1429–1509":"1429–1509","1430–1470":"1430–1470","1430–Female":"1430–Surnud","1440–Female":"1440–Surnud","1442–Male":"1442–Surnud","1415–1449":"1415–1449","1435–Male":"1435–Surnud","1445–1536":"1445–1536","1396–1452":"1396–1452","1400–1492":"1400–1492","1396":"1396","1440":"1440","1492":"1492","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1536":"1536","1415":"1415","1435":"1435","1424":"1424","1445":"1445","1400":"1400","1442":"1442","1452":"1452","1430":"1430","1509":"1509","1419":"1419","1429":"1429","1449":"1449","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England":"England","Rugge, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1419–1445":"1419–1445","1424–1480":"1424–1480","1424–1509":"1424–1509","1429–1509":"1429–1509","143